Bittrex API

The aim of the project is to collect as precise as possible exchanges rates and other information on crypto-currencies (top 100) from their day of creation until today, in order to build potentially behavior models.

For that, having as much information as possile might enable us to build models, however exchanges rates are depending on a potentially infinite number of parameters (individual behaviors, medias, economic growth, etc) for which collecting data might be a incredible amount of work.

So the first idea is to compare historical prices of different cryptocurrencies.

Kaggle gives an interesting data set that shows historical daily prices of top 100 currencies. https://www.kaggle.com/natehenderson/top-100-cryptocurrency-historical-data This dataset is light (only a few MB), however, daily prices might be not precise enough to find out interesting behavior models.

So, the second idea is to see if it is possible to collect more precise data thanks to APIs.

Since I am trading on Bittrex.com, the first idea was to see what kind of information we can get from the Bittrex API (cryptocurrencies market platform)

https://bittrex.com/Home/Api

Ideally, managing to get the historical exchange rate (on a 30 min timestamp basis for example) of all cryptocurrencies on the platform from their day of creation until now would be perfect.

library(jsonlite)
library(glue)
library(httr)

We are gonna try the method /public/getmarkets

url <- glue("https://bittrex.com/api/v1.1/public/getmarkets")
  
res <- GET(url)
  
content(res)

Now lets try the method /public/getticker

Used to get the current tick values for a market.

Parameters parameter required description market required a string literal for the market (ex: BTC-LTC) Request: https://bittrex.com/api/v1.1/public/getticker

url <- glue("https://bittrex.com/api/v1.1/public/getticker?market=BTC-USDT")
  
res <- GET(url)
  
content(res)

Unfortunately it seems that the requests on this API cannot give us historical prices data.

The github links given on the website seem not to be able to give historical data either:

https://github.com/mwerner/bittrex https://github.com/toorop/go-bittrex https://github.com/ericsomdahl/python-bittrex

So, I look for other sources and checked another API platform:

https://www.cryptocompare.com/api/#-api-data-pricehistorical-

But here the historical data are also daily prices. The only advantage compared to the kaggle dataset is up-to-date data. But the effort to grasp the info from the API in order to have only one more month of historical data (kaggle data stops on the 22nd of september), seems quite big for the moment. Consequently this will be done only after a first test on the kaggle dataset. Once a shiny app is created, if there is time left, it will be used to implement a direct connexion to this API.

To see the fisrt test with CSV files download and see Test with CSV files.Rmd

After a few aptempts it appeared that it is not potentially much easier than using an API. I found the potential other API sources:

Other sources:

https://bitcoincharts.com/about/markets-api/ https://bravenewcoin.com/api/digital-currency-historical-data/ https://coinmetrics.io/data-downloads/ https://www.coindesk.com/category/features/data-analysis/

Potentially interesting API to explore:

https://poloniex.com/public?command=returnChartData&currencyPair=BTC_ETH&start=1435699200&end=9999999999&period=14400

https://poloniex.com/exchange#btc_eth https://poloniex.com/exchange#usdt_btc

One needs to edit the timestamps in the API to get a different snapshot. And edit the period to adjust the details. https://opendata.stackexchange.com/questions/6884/cryptocurrency-historical-prices

https://www.quandl.com/data/BNC2-BNC-Digital-Currency-Indexed-EOD https://www.quandl.com/data/BNC1-BNC-Liquid-Index https://www.quandl.com/collections/markets/bitcoin-data

Here the most complete API for historical data seems to be the Poloniex one.

To see the test on the Poloniex API download and see Test with Poloniex API

Here we see that the date is in a UTC seconds format. We need a library to convert it in normal dates. The library anytime can help us.
